<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-568-438  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 568 438.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Networking Management  June 1990 v8 n6 p90(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How to future-proof your LAN wiring system. (local area network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pryma, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Wiring system designers must design a wiring scheme that is usableduring the 40 to 60 year life-span of a building.andP;  The designershould design the vertical wiring between wiring closets and thehorizontal wiring to wall plates so they do not need to bereplaced.andP;  Care should be taken to choose the proper system, onethat will accommodate changes in the communications requirementsof the building's tenants.andP;  In use today are a number ofstructured wiring systems that use both fiber-optic and coppertwisted-pair wire; these systems provide full communicationscapacity now and in the foreseeable future.andP;  Copper cables provideISDN, Ethernet, and token-ring capabilities; fiber-optics permitthe systems to evolve into Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI)operating at 100-Mbps.andP;  Benefits of fiber include immunity tointerference, low loss, large bandwidth.andP;  Network managers candesign a cost-effective wiring system that will work now and inthe future by combining careful planning with knowledge ofavailable cable types, cable specifications, system design, andregulations governing usage.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Network ManagementFiber OpticsLocal Area NetworksTwisted PairCommunications CircuitsFiber Distributed Data Interface Standard.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   The status of twisted-pair cable specifications. (table)ATandamp;T's structured wiring system, Systimax. (chart)Performance levels of twisted-pair cabling. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>